ðŸ”¹ First, Important Understanding
When we create a VPC & Subnets 
ðŸ‘‰ By default, every subnet is private.
That means:
 Instances inside the subnet cannot directly access the internet.
To make a subnet public, we use an Internet Gateway (IGW).

ðŸ”¹ What is an Internet Gateway?
An Internet Gateway (IGW) is a horizontally scaled, highly available AWS-managed component that:
- Enables communication between VPC and the Internet
- Performs 1:1 NAT for public IP addresses (will talk about NAT later)
- Allows inbound and outbound internet traffic
ðŸ’¡ Think of it as the bridge between your VPC and the public internet.

ðŸ”¹ Important Rule
âœ”ï¸ One VPC can have only one IGW attached at a time
âœ”ï¸ One IGW can be attached to only one VPC at a time

ðŸ”¹ How It Works (Step-by-Step)
1ï¸âƒ£ Create an Internet Gateway
2ï¸âƒ£ Attach the IGW to the VPC
3ï¸âƒ£ Create a custom Route Table for public subnets
4ï¸âƒ£ Edit routes inside the Route Table, Add default route pointing to IGW i.e 
ðŸ‘‰ If traffic does not match any specific CIDR block, send it to the Internet Gateway.
5ï¸âƒ£ Associate the public subnet with this route table
Now the subnet becomes a public subnet.

ðŸ”¹ Very Important: Public IP Requirement
Resources created inside that subnet:
1ï¸âƒ£ By default, instances get a private IP address
2ï¸âƒ£ To access the internet, they must have a public IP address
Make sure:
âœ”ï¸ â€œAuto-assign Public IPv4â€ is enabled
